              <div class=3D"subsection">
                <h3>Description</h3>
                <p>Quaternions are used to represent rotations.</p>
              </div>
              <div class=3D"subsection">
        <p>A quaternion is a four-tuple of real numbers {x,y,z,w}. A quater=
nion is a mathematically convenient alternative to the euler angle represen=
tation. You can interpolate a quaternion without experiencing gimbal lock. =
You can also use a quaternion to concatenate a series of rotations into a s=
ingle representation.<br><br>Unity internally uses Quaternions to represent=
 all rotations.<br><br>In most cases, you can use existing rotations from m=
ethods such as <a href=3D"https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Transfor=
m-localRotation.html" aria-label=3D"Go to Transform-localRotation.html">Tra=
nsform.localRotation</a> or <a href=3D"https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptRefer=
ence/Transform-rotation.html" aria-label=3D"Go to Transform-rotation.html">=
Transform.rotation</a> to construct new rotations. For example, use existin=
g rotations to smoothly interpolate between two rotations.
The most used Quaternion functions are as follows:=20
<a href=3D"https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Quaternion.LookRotation=
.html" aria-label=3D"Go to Quaternion.LookRotation.html">Quaternion.LookRot=
ation</a>, <a href=3D"https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Quaternion.A=
ngle.html" aria-label=3D"Go to Quaternion.Angle.html">Quaternion.Angle</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Quaternion.Euler.html"=
 aria-label=3D"Go to Quaternion.Euler.html">Quaternion.Euler</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Quaternion.Slerp.html" aria-la=
bel=3D"Go to Quaternion.Slerp.html">Quaternion.Slerp</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
